<H3> <TI>   Warren Christopher Meets Israeli Foreign Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Warren Christopher Meets Israeli Foreign Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705180394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1715 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705180394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jerusalem, May 17 (XINHUA) -- [Israeli] Foreign 
Minister Shim'on Peres said today that Israel will do utmost to 
push forward the talks with Syria even though there was still no 
sense to have areas of an Israeli-Syrian common announcement on 
the Golan Heights [as received]. 
  Peres was speaking to reporters this afternoon jointly with 
visiting U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher at the 
Foreign Ministry after their half-an-hour talk. 
  "We never denied the difficulties, but on the other side 
there are still hopes of opportunities," Peres said. 
  He thanked Christopher for his continuous effort for peace 
in 
the region. 
  He said Christopher's visits had brought new promises from 
both sides for the negotiations. 
  Christopher, who arrived in Israel Monday [16 May] from 
Damascus, said that "we certainly are making some progress" on 
bringing the Israeli-Syrian negotiations back on track. 
  "But it's a very long road, and we are at the beginning of 
the long road," he said. He did not specify on the progress. 
  "There are detailed discussions on both sides on each of the 
consistent points," he said. "Every meeting I have with them is 
certainly a progress that makes a sense." 
  This morning, Christopher toured the new Palestinian 
autonomous region of Jericho to get first-hand information of 
the developments there. 
  "It is really a thrilling event to see the translation of 
realities on the ground and to see the Palestinians taking 
control of the civil administration," said the U.S. secretary. 
  Christopher is scheduled to hold talks with Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin later today. 
  It is still not clear whether he will return to Damascus or 
just return home Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

