<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cease-Fire for Nagorno-Karabakh Signed in Moscow </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cease-Fire for Nagorno-Karabakh Signed in Moscow </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705062894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0600 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705062894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, May 17 (XINHUA) -- A major new ceasefire 
agreement for the disputed enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh was 
signed by Armenia, Azerbaijan and Nagorno-Karabakh on Monday [16 
May] in Moscow, Russian news agencies reported. 
  The agreement was signed after talks between Azeri Defense 
Minister Mamed Mamedrafi, Armenian Defense Minister Serzhik 
Sarkisyan and Samvel Babayan, the military leader of Nagorno- 
Karabakh. 
  Under the agreement, that was mediated by Russia, Azeri and 
Armenian forces will stop firing at midnight (2000 GMT) on May 
25 and begin a withdrawal, thus forming an exclusion zone. 
  The agreement calls for the warring sides to pull back to 
form an exclusion zone some five to 10 kilometers wide within 
which 49 observation posts can be established. 
  The three officials, along with Russian Defense Minister 
Pavel Grachev, agreed to start posting observers in the region 
on May 24. Peacekeeping forces from the Commonwealth of 
Independent States - the bulk of them 1,800 Russians - will also 
be sent to the area of conflict. 
  In principle, Armenian forces will then start pulling out of 
most of the Azeri territory they occupied in a series of 
sweeping offensives last year. 
  The agreement is to be presented to Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin this week for his approval, ITAR-TASS reported. 
  Nagorno-Karabakh, an autonomous region within Azerbaijan, is 
populated largely by Armenians. 
  The war for control of the region is the most protracted 
ethnic conflict in the former Soviet Union. A senior 
Azerbaijani official disclosed on Saturday that an estimated 
20,000 Azerbaijanis have been killed and a further 50,000 maimed 
since a separatist movement was launched in 1988, which led to 
the declaration of an independent republic in the region in 
September 1991. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

