<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-096 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   All-China Journalists Association Expands Foreign Contacts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    All-China Journalists Association Expands Foreign Contacts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705205294 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0920 
GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1705205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Qu Zhihong (2575 1807 4767)] </F>
  [Excerpt] Beijing, 29 Apr (XINHUA) -- China's reform which 
is being carried out across the country and its omnidirectional 
opening to the outside world have enabled its foreign contacts 
to enjoy extensive development. In recent years, the All-China 
Journalists Association [ACJA] also paid close attention to 
bringing into play its own strong points as a mass organization; 
opened up various channels; promoted mutual understanding and 
exchanges and expanded friendship as well as cooperation between 
Chinese and foreign press circles; studied the experiences in 
journalist work gained by every other country and used them as a 
reference; and made great progress. 
  According to a briefing, the ACJA has received a total of 
148 
delegations of foreign journalists from about 40 countries in 
the past three years. Meanwhile, it sent 43 press delegations 
to visit nearly 30 countries. In having their contacts with 
foreign counterparts closely revolve around two themes, peace 
and development, these delegations helped all the people of 
every other country in the world understand China and improved 
Chinese press circles' understanding of their counterparts in 
every other country through exchanges between press circles. 
  After China resumed diplomatic ties with Indonesia and 
normalized its relations with Vietnam, the ACJA organized in a 
timely manner mutual visits between Chinese journalists and 
their Indonesian and Vietnamese counterparts. In its capacity 
as a mass organization, the ACJA carried out numerous contacts 
with Korean press circles before China established diplomatic 
relations with the ROK. Chinese and Korean journalists 
associations sent formal delegations to visit each other in 
1993. After the disintegration of the Soviet Union and the 
drastic changes in East Europe, Chinese press circles 
established ties or carried out contacts with their counterparts 
in Russia, Romania, Slovakia, Ukraine, Poland, the Czech 
Republic, and Albania. It also increased contacts with the U.S. 
press circles over the past three years. In 1991, it received a 
delegation of the U.S. press industry association which visited 
China at its own expense. In 1992 and 1993, China organized 
four [press] delegations to visit the United States. 
  In compliance with the guidelines of Comrade Deng Xiaoping's 
instruction -- "In our opening up, we not only must develop 
international contacts but also must assimilate international 
experiences," Chinese press delegations paid attention to 
conducting a survey of the state of foreign press media as well 
as their experiences to use them as a reference. After they 
returned home, they wrote summary and brief reports which can be 
used as valuable reference materials in addition to publishing 
many articles on what they had seen and heard. 
  As regards the contacts with the Taiwan, Hong Kong, and 
Macao 
regions, which have a blood relationship with the mainland, 
press circles on both sides closely follow the issue with 
interest. After the ACJA was entrusted to do so by the party 
Central Committee and the State Council in 1985 and 1987, 
respectively, it received Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan 
journalists who visited the mainland. Under the guidance of the 
principles "peaceful reunification" and "one country, two 
systems," it established extensive contacts with press circles 
in Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Macao and promoted two-way exchanges. 
  The ACJA received a total of more than 1,400 well-known 
journalists and figures from Taiwan press circles and more than 
1,700 well-known journalists and figures from Hong Kong and 
Macao press circles over the past three years. With the 
assistance of the ACJA and with its coordination, Taiwan, Hong 
Kong, and Macao journalists traveled all over the motherland and 
participated in the report on the sessions of the National 
People's Congress, the National Committee of the Chinese 
People's Political Consultative Conference, and the 14th 
National CPC Congress and on other important activities, thereby 
enabling the people in the Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Macao regions 
to have a better understanding of the motherland's reform, 
opening up, and investment environment as well as of China's 
5,000-year-old history and culture. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

