<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Cites Senator Dole's Urging MFN Extension for China </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Cites Senator Dole's Urging MFN Extension for China </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705224894 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0741 
GMT 17 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1705224894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, 16 May (XINHUA) -- In addressing the 
Congress on 16 May, U.S. Senate Republican leader Dole urged 
President Clinton to immediately and unconditionally extend 
most-favored nation [MFN] status to China. 
  Dole said: "We only have a few days before the President has 
to decide. If possible, the President absolutely should 
immediately announce that he will unconditionally extend MFN 
status to China." 
  He added: The President "should frankly express what most of 
us have known for a long time: It is infeasible to link trade 
with human rights issues. That policy has already failed. The 
President should admit this and continue to move forward." 
  He reiterated that he does not agree with the measure that 
will disrupt [po huai 4275 0975] trade relations between the two 
countries. He believes that it will only lead to unemployment 
for many Americans and cause U.S. companies to lose the 
opportunity to participate in the world's fastest-growing 
economy. 

</TEXT>

