<H3> <TI>   Holds Talks With Group </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Holds Talks With Group </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705144694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1419 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 17 (XINHUA) -- Jiang Zemin, secretary 
general of Chinese Communist Party (CPC) Central Committee, 
hoped that Sino-Japanese good-neighborly relations and mutually 
beneficial cooperation will be continuously furthered. 
  He made the statement when meeting with a delegation from 
the 
Social Democratic Party of Japan (SDPJ), headed by its 
secretary- general, Kubo Wataru, here today. 
  Jiang, who is also China's president, said: "I have met with 
leaders of your party many times in Beijing and Tokyo," adding 
that constant contacts between leaders of the two parties are 
important for enhancing understanding and friendship. 
  He hoped the SDPJ can further bilateral relations. 
  Jiang noted that the development of good-neighborly 
relations 
and cooperation was not only in the interests of the two peoples 
but also beneficial to peace and development in Asia and the 
world, and so the two countries should further develop such 
relations. 
  Jiang spoke highly of the SDPJ's efforts during the past 
years to promote Sino-Japanese friendship, saying that the SDPJ 
had made important contributions to the normalization of 
Sino-Japanese diplomatic relations and the healthy development 
of bilateral relations. 
  Wataru said that his party attaches great importance to the 
ties with China, and the treatment of history is a big issue in 
bilateral relations, adding: "We have all along advocated that 
Japan should take a road of peaceful development, and maintain 
and promote friendship between the two countries." 
  He said that the main purpose of their current China visit 
was, through celebrating the tenth anniversary of the 
establishment of relations between the SDPJ and CPC, to further 
bilateral friendly relations. 
  Jiang said that not long ago, there were inharmonious tones 
in Sino-Japanese relations, which was denying history and 
against the will of the two peoples, and should be condemned. 
  He continued that only rightful treatment of the past and 
advocacy of Sino-Japanese friendship could make the two peoples 
maintain friendship from generation to generation. 
  Wataru said that the SDPJ, in power or out of power, would 
continue to conduct friendly exchanges with the CPC and the 
Chinese people, so as to make efforts for peace and development 
in Asia and the world. 
  Li Shuzheng, head of the International Liaison Department of 
the CPC Central Committee, was present at the meeting. 
  Yesterday morning, Li held talks with the Japanese visitors 
on furthering relations between the two parties. 
  Wu Xueqian, vice-chairman of the national committee of the 
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, met with the 
Japanese guests here this evening and hosted a banquet in their 
honor. 

</TEXT>

