<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sri Lankan Opposition Leader To Decide on Key Party Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sri Lankan Opposition Leader To Decide on Key Party Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605063994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0609 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605063994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Colombo, May 16 (XINHUA) -- Sri Lanka's main 
opposition leader Mrs. Sirimavo Bandaranaike will soon decide 
whether she or her daughter Chandrika should run as Freedom 
Party (SLFP) candidate at the next presidential election, party 
sources here said today. 
  Bandaranaike was unanimously named party presidential 
candidate few months ago but the 78-year old leader who was 
twice premier in the island country is under increasing pressure 
to step down in favor of her 47-year old daughter Chandrika who 
is now the chief minister of Western Province. 
  But no one in the decision making Central Committee of the 
party will openly ask Mrs. Bandaranake to withdraw from the 
candidacy, and it is very much at her discretion to continue as 
party presidential candidate or to step down in favor of her 
daughter, a party insider told XINHUA. 
  Chandrika's chances as potential leader of the main 
opposition freedom party received a new boost when she led her 
party into a sweeping win at the March 23 southern provincial 
election, the SLFP's only formidable election success against 
the ruling United National Party (UNP) for last seventeen years. 
  Her chances in the party to succeed the mother also 
increased 
greatly since brother Anura Bandaranaike, her only challenger 
crossed over to the government after much infighting, and 
accepted higher education portfolio few months ago. 
  A national level meeting of SLFP's different organizational 
bodies and elected members to be convened next week is expected 
to discuss party strategy for next presidential election due 
before December this year, and Mrs. Bandaranaike is likely to 
make an important speech there, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

