Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taiwan Police Boats Patrol Spratly Islands </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taiwan Police Boats Patrol Spratly Islands </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605095394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0939 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 16 (XINHUA) -- Two Taiwan police cruise 
boats recently completed patrols of the Nansha [Spratly] 
Islands, the first such move by Taiwan Police, according to 
reports from Taiwan. 
  The primary task for the cruise by the two police 400-DWT 
Boats was to survey the waters around Taiping Island and chart 
routes from Taiwan to Taiping in order to provide important 
information for the establishment of a peacekeeping force on the 
island and facilitate future sails for ships and fleets. 
  According to the reports, on patrol were two associate 
geology chief engineers of the "China Petroleum Corporation" in 
Taiwan. They were to survey sites with exploitable oil and gas. 
Meanwhile, a fisheries research boat named "Yuxun No.2" 
carrying 31 oceanology experts joined the cruise. 
  According to reports, the Taiwan regime has reiterated that 
the Nansha Islands are an inseparable part of China and 
sovereignty belongs to China. In December 1992, the Taiwan 
regime set up "the South China Sea Group" and mapped out an 
"outline on South China Sea policies." Such policies aim to 
firmly safeguard the sovereign rights in the South China Sea. 
In September 1993, a large-scale, high-level symposium was held 
on the South China Sea, called by Taiwan's "Ministry of the 
Interior". Addressing the opening ceremony, Lien Chan noted 
that no country can deny the fact that the islands in the South 
China Sea belong to China whether in legal principle or from the 
historical perspective. Officials from Taiwan's "Ministry of 
the Interior" said that Taiwan will continue irregular patrols 
to the South China Sea in the future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-50411 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi095_v_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-095 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Associations Threaten To Stop Some U.S. Imports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Associations Threaten To Stop Some U.S. Imports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705095994 Taipei Voice of Free China in English 0200 GMT 
15 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1705095994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei Voice of Free China </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News" program] </F>
  [Text] Taiwan's importers of corn and soybeans, 
retaliating against the U.S. ban on import of wildlife products, 
threatened Friday [13 May] to take their business worth about $1 
billion a year away from the United States. The Taiwan Feed 
Industry Association and the Taiwan Vegetable Oil Manufacturers 
Association lodged protests with Washington's unofficial embassy 
in Taipei over the U.S. ban on wildlife product imports from 
Taiwan. 
  President Bill Clinton announced the ban, worth up to $25 
million a year, last month in response to the island's continued 
trade in products made from endangered tigers and rhinos. 
  A spokesman for the Taiwan Feed Industry Association said if 
there is no goodwill response from the United States, his 
association will give priority to South Africa, Thailand, 
Central American countries, and Australia when buying corn and 
soybeans. The two associations of Taiwan's many importers of 
corn and soybeans buy 5 million and 2 million tons a year. ROC 
[Republic of China] officials have denounced the U.S. move as 
unjust after Mainland China eluded sanctions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

