<DOCNO> FBIS4-50418 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi096_h_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-096 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Ruihuan Visits Northern European Countries </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Ruihuan Visits Northern European Countries </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets Danish Prime Minister </H4>

<F P=102> OW1605151594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1434 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Copenhagen, May 16 (XINHUA) -- Danish Prime 
Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen today told Li Ruihuan, chairman of 
the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political 
Consultative Conference (CPPCC), that he was deeply impressed by 
China's economic development. 
  Speaking at their meeting in Copenhagen, the Danish prime 
minister also stressed that danish-Chinese relations are "very 
good", expressing his optimism about the future. 
  Li arrived in the Danish capital on Friday for a four-day 
visit. 
  He told Rasmussen that China is very happy to see the two 
countries enjoying a deepened understanding which has resulted 
in a fruitful cooperation in trade and economic matters due to 
expanded exchanges at senior levels. 
  At the request of Rasmussen, Li gave an outline of China's 
political system reform, its socialist democratic politics and 
the people's political consultative conference. 
  While meeting this morning with Mimi Jakobasen, Danish 
industry minister [title as received], Li said he hoped Denmark 
would further its trade cooperation with China, utilizing its 
advanced knowledge in electronics, food processing, the chemical 
industry, medicine and environmental protection. 
  Jakobasen said Danish business circles are very interested 
in 
investing and doing business in China since the two countries 
have respective advantages in different sections and the 
potential for cooperation is very large. 
  She expressed the wish that the chairman's visit will have a 
positive influence on trade and economic exchanges between the 
two countries. 
  Li Ruihuan also met today Ivar Hansen, the first 
vice-president of the Danish Parliament, and Kirsten Jacobs who 
is the fourth vice- president of the parliament. 

</TEXT>

