<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tong Zhiguang on Purpose of Export-Import Bank </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tong Zhiguang on Purpose of Export-Import Bank </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705123194 Beijing Central Television Program One Network 
in Mandarin 1100 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1705123194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing Central Television Program One Network 
in Mandarin 1100 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on interview with Tong Zhiguang, board chairman of </F>
the Import and Export Bank of China, by Liu Shaobo (0491 1421 
0590), station correspondent identified by caption; place and 
date not given -- passages within quotation marks recorded; from 
the "National News Hookup" program] 
  [Text] To promote the sustained, rapid, and healthy 
development of China's foreign trade, the State Council has 
decided to set up the Import and Export Bank of China. A 
station correspondent interviewed Tong Zhiguang, board chairman 
of the Import and Export Bank of China. [Video shows Tong 
Zhiguang, in a dark Western business suit, seated at a desk in 
his office; a male reporter is seen sitting across the desk and 
holding out a microphone. As Tong speaks, the camera zooms in 
to show medium closeup shots of him.] 
  [Liu Shaobo] "Chairman Tong, why did we establish the Import 
and Export Bank of China?" 
  [Tong] "The State Council's decision to set up the China 
Export and Import Bank is geared to the demands of our country's 
current implementation of a socialist market economy. For many 
years, our country has achieved tremendous results in exports 
but our main exports have been agricultural, sideline, 
indigenous, and specialty products. We now face the task of 
upgrading and renewing our export products by exporting more 
technology-intensive products. A review of the status of our 
country's industries shows that our machinery and electronics 
products and turnkey equipment are highly competitive in this 
respect. The bank's establishment will create excellent 
conditions for the export of such products. The bank will 
extend credit on the export of such goods, so as to create a 
strong banking support system for upgrading and improving their 
quality." 
  Chairman Tong Zhiguang told the reporter: The Import and 
Export Bank of China's capital funds are allocated from the 
state coffers. The bank is managed on the basis of 
self-sufficiency and break-even concepts, and along the lines of 
enterprise administration; however, it is not an institution 
that provides free allocations. Operationally, it is directed 
and supervised by the Finance Ministry, the Ministry of Foreign 
Trade and Economic Cooperation, and the People's Bank of China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-50429 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi096_n_94008" </HT>


