<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Anti-Inflation Measures Expected Near Jun-Jul </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Anti-Inflation Measures Expected Near Jun-Jul </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1705011694 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in Chinese 1342 
GMT 14 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1705011694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 14 May (ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE)--Prices are 
currently one of the greatest concerns of the Chinese people. 
To further tighten price management, concerned departments are 
planning to continue increasing the force of regulation and 
control. Some relevant measures are expected to be unveiled 
around June and July. 
  These measures are understood to include: First, strict 
controls over the scale of fixed-asset investment, firmly 
cutting and stopping a number of construction projects, no more 
approval this year for large and medium-sized infrastructure 
projects not listed in the "Eighth Five-Year Plan," and strict 
controls over high-class office buildings, villas, and upmarket 
entertainment facilities. 
  Second, strict control over the excessive growth of 
consumption funds. There are plans to slow down the growth rate 
of consumption funds by reducing corporate consumption power 
with methods such as strengthening the finances of enterprises 
and nonprofit-making institutions and taxation and controlling 
and cutting back administrative expenditure, while turning the 
purchasing power and consumption of urban and rural residents 
into savings and mid and long-term investment. 
  Third, make great efforts to pursue agriculture and "food 
basket" projects, increase the cultivated area for major 
agricultural products, such as grains and cotton, and ensure 
that materials and funds supporting agriculture reach their 
destination. 
  Fourth, make further efforts at building and perfecting 
means 
to regulate and control prices and markets, including reserve 
systems for several key commodities and a risk fund system in 
order to increase the state's regulatory and control powers. 
  Fifth, arrange well this year's production and supply of key 
commodities. To stabilize grain and oil prices, the state will, 
if necessary, release quantities of reserve grain and oil. 
  Furthermore, the State Planning Commission is drafting rules 
and regulations against profiteering. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

