<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Trade Continues Double-Digit Growth </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Trade Continues Double-Digit Growth </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1705092394 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 17 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK1705092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [China Daily News: "Growth Boom Continues in Foreign Trade"] </F>
  [Text] China's foreign trade has continued its 
double-digit growth in the first four months of this year, to 
hit a total volume of $57.84 billion, up 21 per cent over the 
same period of last year. customs officials said. 
  The export growth rate grew faster than that of imports, 
indicating that the macro-economic and reform measures adopted 
since late last year have paid off, according to officials in 
the General Administration of Customs (GAC). 
  Foreign-funded enterprises continued to set the pace in 
trade, as their exports and imports reached $21.33 billion, a 
46.9 per cent increase and accounting for nearly 37 per cent of 
the national trade volume. 
  During the January-April period, China's total imports grew 
by 20.3 per cent, amounting to $29.79 billion, while gross 
exports increased 22 per cent, hitting a total of $28.04 billion. 
  The export growth rate was a 3.3 per cent rise over that in 
the year's first quarter, according to statistics from the GAC. 
  This, the GAC officials said, also signaled that the 
government has put an end to the trend of a weak export growth 
against a runaway import boom. 
  However, in the four-month period, China's foreign trade 
still saw a deficit of $1.75 billion, only $20 million less than 
the same period of the previous year, the GAC officials said. 
  General merchandise exports recorded a 30.5 per cent lift 
with a total volume of $14.36 billion, which accounted for over 
half of all exports, while the processing trade maintained a 
high growth rate of over 23 per cent, totalling nearly $11.3 
billion. 
  But exports and imports through barter and border trade, 
respectively, plummeted 55 and 26 per cent, standing at a total 
of only $1.08 billion. 
  In the first four months this year, there were some major 
changes in the mix of China's exports as manufactured products 
witnessed a sharp rise of 25.6 per cent to $23.2 billion, 
accounting for 82.7 per cent of all exports. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-50445 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi096_n_94024" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-096 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Customs Reports Exports Growing Faster Than Imports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Customs Reports Exports Growing Faster Than Imports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605134894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1314 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 16 (XINHUA) -- China's exports grew 
faster than its imports in the first four months of this year. 
  This was revealed by the latest statistics from the Chinese 
Customs Department, which showed that the country's foreign 
trade volume was 21.1 percent greater than in the same period 
last year, with a total trade volume of 57.84 billion U.S. 
dollars. 
  Imports in the period totalled 29.79 billion U.S. dollars 
(up 
20.3 percent over the same period of 1993), while exports 
amounted to 28.04 billion U.S. dollars (up 22 percent). 
  That China's export growth rate is higher than the import 
one 
is attributed by experts to a series of macro-control measures 
and national foreign trade reform started in the latter half of 
last year and at the beginning of this year, in response to a 
then- growing trade deficit. 
  Japan is still the largest of all of China's trade partners: 
the bilateral trade volume reached 11.03 billion U.S. dollars, 
(up 34.9 percent), and made up 20.7 percent of the country's 
total foreign trade volume. 
  China's other large trade partners include Hong Kong, the 
European Community, the United States and Taiwan. 
  The trade volume of China's joint ventures reached 21.33 
billion U.S. dollars (up 46.9 percent), a much higher rise than 
the country's average foreign trade growth rate. The figure 
represents 36.9 percent of China's total foreign trade volume, 
compared with the 30.5 percent which this sector achieved in the 
same period last year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

