<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   State To Lift Import Restrictions for Commodities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State To Lift Import Restrictions for Commodities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1505043294 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 0341 GMT 
14 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1505043294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 14 (CNS) -- China has decided to lift 
restrictions on some commodities imported to China. 
  By the end of last year, China had canceled requirements of 
a 
permit for a batch of imported commodities, including steel 
material, steel billet, waste steel, plasters, drilling tools, 
coffee and its products, airplanes for civil purpose, fruits and 
black-and-white kinescopes. 
  Restrictions on the following commodities to be imported to 
the country will also be canceled by the end of this year. They 
are: chemical fibre clothing, beer and grape wine, plant oil, 
wood and wood pulp, ABS resin, sodium chloride, demolition 
material for civil purposes, synthetic glue, plywood, petroleum, 
some chemical products, computers, X-ray machines, some medical 
equipment, air- conditioners of power over 21.4 kilowatts and 
cooling compressors of power over 22.5 kilowatts. 
  Permits required of some imports which will be lifted by the 
end of 1995 cover such commodities as duplicating machines, 
integrated circuits, films, some kinds of chemical products, 
wines, air-conditioners with cooling equipment being not yet 
installed and car chassis. 
  Permits for pesticide and carbonate beverage will be lifted 
by the end of 1996. 

</TEXT>

