<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai Mayor on New Retirement System </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai Mayor on New Retirement System </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705025194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0231 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705025194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, May 17 (XINHUA) -- Under the Retirement 
Insurance Law issued in April, Shanghai's 4.01 million workers 
will enjoy an old-age pension as long as they have paid a 
premium for a long enough period. 
  Each of them has a fixed account recording how much premium 
he or she hands in, and each will keep the account for good, no 
matter whether he or she switches jobs, loses a job or moves to 
another locality. 
  The new system covers all staff in the city's 
administrations 
and enterprises, excluding foreign personnel in overseas-funded 
companies and some workers whose pensions are specially arranged 
by the government. 
  Shanghai, China's biggest metropolis with a population of 13 
million, has over two million people above the age of 60. 
  Mayor Huang Ju said that Shanghai aims to set up a 
scientific 
and socialized retirement insurance system. 
  In accordance with the new regulations, individuals should 
pay three per cent of their monthly salary as premium. The 
proportion will increase with the pace of growing incomes. 
  And the amount of old-age pension will depend on the sum of 
premiums paid by individuals and will be adjusted in line with 
the cost of living index. 
  People who work for private businesses can also benefit from 
the system. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

