<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Roundup' Views Shanghai's Economic Performance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Roundup' Views Shanghai's Economic Performance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705064494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0608 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705064494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Roundup: Performance of Shanghai's Economy Improves"] </F>
  [Text] Shanghai, May 17 (XINHUA) -- Known as "China's 
economic barometer," Shanghai's economy continues to operate 
smoothly despite such adverse factors as raw materials price 
hikes, shortage of fund supply and sluggish market. 
  According to the municipal statistics bureau, Shanghai's 
gross domestic product (GDP) this year is expected to surpass 
the 13-percent increase of last year and reach the year's target. 
  Although industry, of which the output accounts for 60 
percent of the GDP, slipped early this year, it began to pick up 
in March, and jumped by 16 percent in April in comparison with 
the same period of last year. The ratio between sales volume 
and output reached 97.5 percent last month. 
  As a result of streamlining the foreign trade structure, 
improving the mechanism for encouraging exports and the 
municipal government's policy of promoting foreign trade, 
Shanghai exported a record 2.46 billion U.S. dollars-worth of 
goods in the first four months of this year, up 26.6 percent 
over the same period last year. 
  The city's improving investment conditions have aroused the 
interest of foreign business people, who set up 1,256 
foreign-funded projects with the approval of the municipal 
government in the January-April period. 
  These projects involved a combined investment of 2.89 
billion 
U.S. dollars, and some of them were funded by trans-national 
corporations. 
  However, a local official said there are still problems in 
the economy. 
  He analysed the situation as follows: "One third of 
state-owned enterprises suffer from losses which are caused by 
poor enterprise management, price hikes for raw materials and 
the unification of the dual exchange rate system. They result 
in a rise in production costs and hurt the enterprises badly." 
  Other factors include shortages of funds, inflation and 
sluggish markets. 
  The official noted that though Shanghai's inflation rate is 
lower than those of many other major cities in the country, it 
still affects the living standard of the lower-income people, 
retired people in particular. 
  However, experts here agree that Shanghai's economy is 
developing steadily thanks to the high input into the economy 
over the past few years, the increasing rationality of the 
economic structure, and the smooth reforms of the tax, banking 
and social security systems. 
  In line with the economic situation in the first four months 
of this year, the municipal government has decided to rearrange 
its credits and loans with the focus on supporting key 
enterprises, especially major foreign trade enterprises. 
  It urged industrial departments to take the marketing of 
industrial products as the most important task in order to boost 
production. 
  Meanwhile, related government departments have begun to help 
enterprises in the red to change their operational mechanism and 
make up deficits and increase surpluses in the process of market 
competition step by step. 
  In addition, the city is looking for a new way to make an 
overall opening to the outside world while continuously 
implementing the reform measures. 
  Economists believe that the municipal quota of a 12-percent 
growth in the economy and striving to attain 15 percent this 
year can be obtained on the condition that the macro-economic 
environment does not deteriorate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

