<H3> <TI>   Shanghai's Banking Services Maturing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai's Banking Services Maturing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605073994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0640 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605073994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, May 16 (XINHUA) -- Shanghai's banking 
setup is developing in a healthy direction this year, according 
to Mao Yingliang, president of the Shanghai branch of the 
People's Bank of China. 
  The savings deposits in the various banks in this, China's 
largest economic center, increased by 22.63 billion yuan in the 
first four months of this year, an increase of 85 percent over 
the same period of last year. 
  Mao noted that Shanghai has made rational use of credits and 
loans to ensure the development of the key state capital 
projects and its new pillar industries, including motor 
vehicles, telecommunications, chemicals, machinery and 
electrical appliances, and the basic industries of power, 
textiles and steel products, as well as people's daily 
necessities. 
  The China foreign exchange center, which opened for service 
here April 4, has been linked up with 12 cities, and concluded 
transactions worth a total of three billion U.S. dollars and 
2.66 billion Hong Kong dollars so far. 
  The transactional volume of the Shanghai Stock Exchange in 
the first four months of this year amounted to 243 billion 
yuan-worth, up 58.8 percent over the same period of last year. 
  The interbank loans in Shanghai climbed to 56.24 billion 
yuan 
in the January-April period. 
  At present, the city has more than 90 foreign-funded banking 
institutions and representative offices. Their capital was 
2.892 billion U.S. dollars by the end of March this year, an 
increase of 16 percent over the same period of last year. 

</TEXT>

