<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hubei Puts Prices of Daily Necessities Under Control </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hubei Puts Prices of Daily Necessities Under Control </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1805025394 Wuhan Hubei People's Radio Network in Mandarin 
1000 GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1805025394 </F>
<F P=104>  Wuhan Hubei People's Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Our province has put the prices of residents' basic 
daily necessities and services under overall control beginning 
early May. 
  In light of our province's actual conditions, in addition to 
the 20 items of goods and services whose prices and charges 
should be subject to overall price control as stipulated by the 
State Council, that is, wheat flour, polished long-grained 
nonglutinous rice, polished round-grained nonglutinous rice, 
edible plant oils, meat, eggs, milk, salt, sugar, soy sauce, 
detergents, coal for domestic use, liquefied petroleum gas, gas 
for domestic use, rents, running water charges, tuition fees and 
extras, child-care fees, medical care fees, and in-city public 
transport fares, the provincial government decided to put the 
prices of medicines under control. Price bureaus of various 
prefectures, autonomous prefectures, counties, and cities are 
encouraged to work out lists of additional specific items to be 
put under price control and report them to local governments for 
implementation. 
  Since the prices of our province's 21 items subject to price 
control have mostly been liberalized, to ensure the active 
control of commodity prices by means of price control, the 
provincial government has worked out specific stipulations on 
the division of authority over and measures for price control. 
It is learned that price control over the 21 items of 
residents' daily necessities and service charges has been 
carried out in different ways in accordance with the degree of 
impact on residents and the existing price management. These 
are mainly monitoring and guiding the trend of commodity prices 
by regulating the filing system, collecting information about 
commodity price changes and promulgating rules and regulations, 
providing information for macrodecisionmaking, introducing 
buying and selling price differential control and wholesale and 
retail price differential control to the circulation links of 
some commodities, and applying moderate administrative 
intervention in the behavior of increasing the prices of some 
commodities by introducing a report-for-approval system at the 
provincial and city levels or adopting interim price limiting 
measures. 
  The provincial government stressed: Price control should be 
carried out at the same time as the enterprises' decisionmaking 
power to set their own prices is respected. All producing and 
operating enterprises should properly handle the relationship 
between reform, development, and stability. In setting their 
prices, they should take it as a prerequisite to maintain market 
and social stability and rigorously standardize their own price 
readjusting behavior. At the same time, they have the duty to 
report readjustments of the prices of residents' basic daily 
necessities and service charges to their superior price 
departments for approval and recording in accordance with state 
stipulations. Subordinate governments also have the duty to 
report readjustments of the prices of basic daily necessities 
and service charges to their superior governments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

