<DOCNO> FBIS4-50494 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi095_v_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-095 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chien Says Li's Trip Strengthened Foreign Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chien Says Li's Trip Strengthened Foreign Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605141194 Taipei CNA in English 1333 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605141194 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 16 (CNA) -- Foreign Minister Fredrick 
F. Chien said Monday [16 May] that President Li's 13-day, 
four-nation visit has contributed greatly to the strengthening 
of Taiwan's relationships with both friendly countries and those 
countries with which it does not maintain formal diplomatic ties. 
  Chien, who was a member of President Li's entourage during 
the overseas trip, made the remarks at a press conference. 
  President Li returned home Monday afternoon after visiting 
Nicaragua, Costa Rica, South Africa and Swaziland. 
  Chien said that Li had met with around 30 heads of state 
during his stay in South Africa. 
  He said he would like to use the Chinese proverb, "I will do 
what I should do no matter how difficult it is," to describe 
what Li had done and his dedication in expanding Taiwan's 
diplomatic arena. 
  Chien, however, denied news reports that Li met with 
Singaporean Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong during his stopover at 
Singapore's Chang Kai-shek International Airport on Monday 
morning. 
  He said Li only had a 30-minute meeting with Ker Sin Tze 
[name and title as received], Singapore's state minister for 
information, arts, and education. 

</TEXT>

