<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Notes Christopher Ends Visit to Syria </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Notes Christopher Ends Visit to Syria </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1805180594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1739 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1805180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Damascus, May 18 (XINHUA) -- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher left here this afternoon for Egypt, winding 
up his visit to Syria in a shuttle diplomacy to expedite the 
peace process. 
  Christopher, who arrived here from Tel Aviv earlier today, 
held talks with Syrian President Hafiz al-Asad on ways of 
bringing closer the viewpoints of Syria and Israel to narrow 
their differences over restoring Syria's Golan Heights. 
  Syrian Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' and U.S. Middle East 
peace coordinator Dennis Ross attended the talks. 
  Diplomatic sources here said that Christopher is shuttling 
between Israel and Syria to seek common ground and help iron out 
hurdles still on the way to peace. 
  The sources said that the talks Christopher had in Tel Aviv 
Tuesday [17 May] and in Damascus today have not made tangible 
headway in bringing their differences closer. 
  Christopher, who did not give a press briefing on his talks, 
was seen off by al-Shar' at the airport. 
  Syria's presidential spokesman Jibran Kourieh [name as 
received] said after Christopher's departure that "the 
differences remained wide." 
  "The president reiterated Syria's position and its adherence 
to the basis of the peace process in accordance with U.N. 
Security Council resolutions which call on Israel to fully 
withdraw" from territories occupied in 1967," Kourieh said. 
[quotation marks as received] 

</TEXT>

