<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Orders Continuation of Military Service System </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton Orders Continuation of Military Service System </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905065494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0620 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905065494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, May 18 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton today ordered peacetime draft registration and the 
selective service system to be continued, said the White House. 
  "It is essential to our national security to continue draft 
registration and the selective service system (SSS)," Clinton 
wrote in letters to Congress, said White House spokeswoman Dee 
Dee Myers in a statement. 
  Clinton argued that the SSS and the registration provide "a 
hedge against unforeseen threats and a relatively low-cost 
`insurance policy' against our underestimating the maximum level 
of threat we expect our armed forces to face." 
  "Terminating the SSS and draft registration now could send 
the wrong signal to our potential enemies who are watching for 
signs of U.S. resolve," he warned. 
  He added that "it is increasingly important" to maintain the 
link between the all volunteer force and the U.S. society at 
large at a time when fewer and fewer people have direct military 
experience. 
  In January, Clinton ordered the National Security Council to 
review the policy. 
  The process involved representatives from the Office of the 
Secretary of State, the Pentagon inspector general and the 
Office of Management and Budget and SSS. 
  The decision, in effect, rejected a Pentagon conclusion 
earlier this year that ending draft registration would pose no 
risk to national security. 
  Clinton also urged lawmakers to support the administration's 
1995 budget request of 23 million dollars for the SSS. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

