<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Lanqing Predicts Imports To Eventually Reach $1 Trillion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Lanqing Predicts Imports To Eventually Reach $1 Trillion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905104994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1038 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905104994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Singapore, May 19 (XINHUA) -- China is expected to 
import more than one trillion U.S. dollars worth of goods in the 
upcoming years before the end of the century, Chinese Vice 
Premier Li Lanqing predicted here today. 
  He made the projection while addressing the international 
conference of "Waves of the Future - ASEAN, Vietnam, and China: 
Opportunities for World Business". 
  More than 800 delegates, mostly high ranking government 
leaders, successful businessmen, and policy researchers, from 21 
countries and regions around the world are attending the 
three-day conference, which started on Tuesday. 
  "We expect that China's total imports through the years to 
the end of the century will top one trillion U.S. dollars," Li 
said in his keynote speech. 
  "Our determination of and confidence in expanding vigorously 
trade and economic contacts with the rest of the world are 
growing steadily during the course of modernization drive," the 
Chinese vice premier added. 
  In the process of reform and opening-up, he said, China's 
external trade and economic cooperation have indicated a good 
trend of development since 1978. 
  The annual growth rate of China's foreign trade over the 15 
years averaged 16 percent, higher both than the average growth 
rate of China's GDP and that of the world trade in the same 
period. 
  China's foreign trade volume in 1993 stood at 195.8 billion 
dollars with exports totaling 91.8 billion dollars and imports, 
104 billion dollars, he said, noting that China's position in 
world trade moved from the 32nd place in 1978 to the 11th place 
in 1993. 
  Meanwhile, the share of China's exports in the total exports 
of the world was 0.75 percent in 1978 and it accounted for 2.5 
percent in 1993, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

