<DATE1>  17 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> East Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Macedonian Minister Tells of Losses Due To War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Macedonian Minister Tells of Losses Due To War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705031294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0239 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705031294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Skoplje, May 16 (XINHUA) -- Macedonian Economic 
Minister Petrus Stefanov has expressed the hope that his country 
will see an early end to the war in ex-yugoslavia so that the 
former Yugoslav Republic could be saved more economic losses. 
  The minister told XINHUA recently that Macedonia has 
suffered 
heavy economic loss from the war and the related sanctions 
against Serbia. 
  Macedonia had been the poorest republic among the six 
republics of the former Yugoslavia. About 80 percent of its 
national economy was related to other republics and 45 percent 
of its external trade depended on Serbia, Stefanov said. 
  After the break-up of the former Yugoslavia, and especially 
since the Bosnian conflict, Macedonia's overseas market has 
shrunk sharply. 
  The main railroads and highways to the outside were almost 
paralyzed after the UN sanction resolution against Serbia, which 
was compounded by Greece's imposition in February of an embargo 
on Macedonia. 
  Macedonia's monthly average economic loss now stands at 150 
million U.S. dollars this year, and total losses reached 1.8 
billion dollars in 1993, Stefanov added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

