<H3> <TI>   Literary Figure Said Missing After Interrogation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Literary Figure Said Missing After Interrogation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1905032894 Hong Kong LIEN HO PAO in Chinese 19 May 94 p 9 </F>
<F P=103> HK1905032894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong LIEN HO PAO </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Dispatch" by reporter Tseng Hui-yen (2582 1979 3601): </F>
"CHING HSIANG Editor Chen Dongdong's Whereabouts Is Unknown, His 
Three Colleagues Are Also Subject to Harassment"] 
  [Text] New York, 18 May (LIEN HO PAO)--Bei Ling, a founder 
of the CHING HSIANG magazine who now lives in Boston, the United 
States, disclosed that Chen Dongdong, the magazine's poem editor 
on the mainland, was summoned to the Shanghai Public Security 
Bureau for interrogation last week, and his whereabouts were 
unknown up to 18 May. Meanwhile, three other editors of the 
magazine on the mainland had been harassed by the authorities to 
a varying extent; and the residence of Bei Ling's parents in 
Beijing was searched by public security personnel. Bei Ling has 
already written to the U.S. PEN and the International PEN to 
raise the case and draw their concern to the issue of personal 
freedom of mainland Chinese writers. 
  Bei Ling said: Except for Meng Lang, a well-known vanguard 
poet, who has gone south to avoid trouble early this year, all 
the other four CHING HSIANG editors in Shanghai, namely, Chen 
Dongdong, Chen Zishan, Zhu Dake, and Sun Ganlu, have been 
frequently summoned by the Shanghai Public Security Bureau for 
"interrogation" since early April. They were mainly questioned 
about the participation of any "reactionary elements" abroad in 
the editorial work of CHING HSIANG, any financial contributions 
by such people to the magazine, and Bei Ling's activities during 
his tour of the mainland from late last year to early this year. 
The police also asked Bei Ling's younger brother, who is 
working in Shanghai, to give an detailed account of Bei Ling's 
social contacts in Shanghai. 

</TEXT>

