<H3> <TI>   Shandong To Honor Best-Behaved Prisoners </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shandong To Honor Best-Behaved Prisoners </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1905073494 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 19 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> HK1905073494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Ma Chenguang: "Prisoners Honoured for Good Deeds"] </F>
  [Text] Jinan -- East China's Shandong Province is to 
honour its best-behaved prisoners later this month at its 
second-ever provincial meeting on inmate conduct. 
  About 250 inmates chosen from Shandong's 57,000 convicts at 
prisons and reform-through-labour camps will be honoured for the 
occasion, said Liu Zhengxin, deputy director of the Justice 
Bureau. 
  About a third of them will have their terms reduced or be 
released on parole, Liu added. 
  Those who excel in their work, reeducation study and daily 
life in prisons usually receive better treatment than other 
prisoners. 
  The province hopes the meeting encourages more inmates to 
behave better in prisons and reform-through-labour institutions, 
Liu added. 

</TEXT>

