<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Returned Students Welcomed in Shanghai </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Returned Students Welcomed in Shanghai </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1805143394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1414 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1805143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, May 18 (XINHUA) -- Shanghai now claims 76 
enterprises launched by Chinese students returned from overseas, 
who have been encouraged by preferential policies endorsed by 
the local government. 
  So far, over 1,000 people back from abroad have lined up for 
official approval to set up their own companies. 
  These firms, featuring high technology, are involved in the 
fields of information, advertising, consultancy and tourism. 
Three-quarters of these returned students have masters' degrees 
or doctorates obtained abroad. 
  Doctor Ni Xuanzhong, who has initiated a company of 
"intelligent machines", is trying to develop an innovatory 
scanner for Chinese characters, which can read 400 characters 
per second. 
  Another new product developed by the company is capable of 
linking six pairs of telephone users using just one line, 
relieving the shortage of lines in the region. 
  Doctor Jiang Qinguo, licensed lawyer who studied in New 
York, 
has established a consultancy firm to offer advice and act as 
agent to Chinese and foreign businessmen, at home and abroad. 
  Luo Yan, nationally-renowned actress who has just finished 
eight years of studying in the United States, has invested 
100,000 U.S. dollars to set up an entertainment firm, prompting 
program exchanges with television and broadcasting stations in 
foreign countries. 
  The city has set aside special areas in some development 
zones, wishing that more and more overseas students will bring 
in investment and their knowledge and skills. 

</TEXT>

