<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Efforts Underway to Develop Shaanxi's Coalfields </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Efforts Underway to Develop Shaanxi's Coalfields </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905045094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0318 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905045094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 19 (XINHUA) -- Various preparations 
for construction of the Shenfu-Huanghua project, involving a 
total investment of over 40 billion yuan (about 4.6 billion U.S. 
dollars) are drawing to an end and full-scale construction of 
the project will soon start. 
  The project includes further development of the 
Shenfu-Dongsheng coalfield in northwest China's Shaanxi 
Province, which will have a total production capacity of more 
than 100 million tons a year; construction of the 
Shenfu-Huanghua railway with a total length of 820 km; and 
construction of the Huanghua port on the Bohai Sea in north 
China, which will have an annual handling capacity of 100 
million tons of coal. 
  The project is aimed at transporting the fine-quality coal 
from the Shenfu-Dongsheng coalfield to the eastern part of the 
country. 
  The Shenfu-Dongsheng coalfield already has a yearly 
production capacity of 10 million tons. The second-stage 
development of coal mines with a total annual capacity of 30 
million tons has been listed as one of the 151 national major 
projects for 1994. 
  The Shenmu-Shuoxian section of the Shenfu-Huanghua railway 
has already gone into operation. The design of the electrified 
multiple-track Shuoxian-Huanghua railway has been completed 
thanks to the efforts of over 300 designers over the past 
several months. Now, a 1,000-member survey team is making the 
final survey along the railway line to pave the way for the 
start of the construction. 
  Work on overall design of the Huanghua port is now in full 
swing. Meanwhile, preparations for construction of the 
supplementary projects of the port such as power and water 
supply projects and telecommunications and communications 
networks will soon be completed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

