<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   High Court Cuts Jail Terms of Mainland Hijackers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    High Court Cuts Jail Terms of Mainland Hijackers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905082794 Taipei CNA in English 0811 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905082794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Lilian Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 19 (CNA) -- The Taiwan High Court 
Thursday [19 May] cut the jail terms for two mainland Chinese 
hijackers from 10 years to seven years. 
  Liu Baocai, 24, and Huang Shugang, 30, hijacked a China 
Southern Airlines' Boeing 757 to Taiwan en route from Shenzhen 
to Beijing on April 5, 1993, marking the first of ten mainland 
hijackings in 1993. 
  Liu and Huang were sentenced to 10 years in prison by a 
Taoyuan District Court, but they appealed to the Taiwan High 
Court, and the High Court upheld the sentence. 
  Liu and Huang then appealed to the Supreme Court. The 
Supreme Court returned the case to the Taiwan High Court for 
retrial. On Thursday, the High Court cut their sentences from 
10 to seven years, saying the hijackers deserved leniency 
because they surrendered without resistance. 
  Judge Wang Hsi-pao of the Taiwan High Court told them that 
they could be paroled after serving slightly more than two years 
in jail. 
  Liu and Huang said they would appeal the decision. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

