<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPP Finalizes Constitutional Change Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPP Finalizes Constitutional Change Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1305144494 Taipei CNA in English 1248 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1305144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 13 (CNA) -- The main opposition 
Democratic Progressive Party [DPP] on Friday [13 May] finalized 
its proposal for constitutional change, recommending that the 
Republic of China [ROC] adopt a single-parliament system and do 
away with the National Assembly, among other changes. 
  The DPP's National Assembly Caucus submitted the proposal, 
which is also being supported by several nonpartisan and 
Kuomintang Assembly members, to the National Assembly 
Secretariat. 
  National Assembly members are gathering in Yangmingshan in 
suburban Taipei for a three-month special meeting to consider 
constitutional changes and the nominations of grand justices and 
the head of the Judicial Yuan. 
  Of the DPP's 31-article proposal, only the one that 
recommends election of the ROC president and vice president by 
popular vote is shared by the ruling Kuomintang. 
  Other major points of the DPP proposal include allowing 
national referendums, abolishing existing nuclear power plants, 
judiciary reforms, and doing away with the quota for overseas 
Chinese parliamentary members. 
  The KMT, which controls a majority of assembly seats, has 
decided to push ahead with its own version of constitutional 
changes, including the election of an assembly speaker and vice 
speaker, extension of legislators' tenure from three years to 
four, and granting overseas Chinese the right to vote in the 
presidential election. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

