<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Official Leads Group to APEC Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Official Leads Group to APEC Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905093894 Taipei CNA in English 0757 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905093894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By P.C. Wu and Lilian Wu] </F>
  [Text] Bali, Indonesia, May 18 (CNA) -- More than 100 
delegates from 17 nations and regions are taking part in a 
senior officials meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic 
Cooperation (APEC) forum which opened Wednesday [19 May]. 
  Shen Kuo-hsiung, director of the Foreign Affairs Ministry's 
Department of International Organizations of the Republic of 
China [ROC], led an 18-member ROC delegation to the meeting. 
  Shen said that the three-day meeting will discuss follow-up 
plans for last year's APEC leadership meeting in seattle and the 
agenda for this year's meeting in December. 
  Wisber Loeis, director-general of Foreign Economic Relations 
Affairs of Indonesia's Department of Foreign Affairs, said that 
the meeting will also discuss the development of manpower 
resources, promotion of small and medium-sized enterprises and 
coordination of trade and public construction. 
  Shen said that the participants decided that the APEC 
leadership meeting this year will be held in Bogor, Indonesia. 
The date for the meeting is still not final, but Indonesia has 
proposed the meeting be held Nov. 15. 
  Lin Yi-fu, vice deputy-general of the ROC's Board of Foreign 
Trade, asked participants to fill out a report on the 
development of small and medium-sized enterprises before the end 
of June, so that APEC experts can discuss the issue in a 
September meeting. 
  APEC groups Australia, Brunei, Canada, Mainland China, Hong 
Kong, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, New Zealand, the Philippines, 
Singapore, South Korea, Taiwan, Thailand, Papua New Guinea, 
Mexico and the United States. 

</TEXT>

