<H3> <TI>   KMT, ROK Companies To Purchase Indonesian Banks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    KMT, ROK Companies To Purchase Indonesian Banks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1405140294 Taipei CNA in English 1326 GMT 14 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1405140294 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 14 (CNA) -- The ruling Kuomintang has 
decided to join hands with South Korean companies in buying 
banks in Indonesia in line with the government's "southern 
strategy," Liu Tai-ying, chairman of the KMT [Kuomintang] 
Business Management Committee, said Saturday [14 May]. 
  "We will seek to buy existing banks run by Chinese in 
Indonesia and establish leasing companies to provide financial 
support for the Taiwan businesses there," Liu said. 
  Taiwan-invested businesses in Indonesia mostly rely on 
foreign banks and the Jakarta office of the China Trust 
Commercial Bank for loans. 
  Liu, during his visit to Jakarta in April, approached 
several 
leading conglomerates with the plan and reached a preliminary 
agreement with a South Korean bank in May. 
  Liu also said that in addition to Indonesia, the KMT is also 
planning to buy a bank in Hong Kong before the colony's transfer 
to Mainland China in 1997. 
  He said that the plan to run banks and other financial 
businesses is only part of the party's "all-out" overseas 
investment policy. Manufacturing and trading industries, he 
added, will follow. 

</TEXT>

