<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chairman on Direct Transportation Links With China </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chairman on Direct Transportation Links With China </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905055994 Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network in Mandarin 2300 GMT 7 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1905055994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] Speaking yesterday [7 May] at a seminar on 
mainland-related economic and trade policy and cross-strait 
transportation sponsored by the [words indistinct] Junior 
Chamber in Taichung City, Huang Kun-hui, chairman of the 
Mainland Affairs Council under the Executive Yuan, said: As 
part of our plans to build Taiwan into a business center in the 
Asia-Pacific region, we do not exclude the possibility of 
establishing direct transportation links with Mainland China. 
However, we should not end up turning Shanghai into a business 
center following the establishment of such links. Now is not 
the time to foster wide-ranging transportation links. 
  Huang Kun-hui said: Direct cross-strait transportation can 
indeed reduce the cost and time of shipping containers. 
However, since our country and Communist China are in a state 
of hostility, the unconditional establishment of such links will 
amount to an acknowledgement that any direct routes thus 
established are domestic routes in Communist China. This will 
make it difficult to clarify to other nations that our country 
is not a province of China. Also, direct transportation 
services will affect our country's alert status. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

