Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hong Kong Affairs Adviser on Passport Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hong Kong Affairs Adviser on Passport Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1805132594 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1042 GMT 
18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1805132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, May 18 (CNS) -- Member of the National 
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative 
Conference (CPPCC) and Hong Kong Affairs Adviser, Mr. Yu 
Kwok-chun, speaking in an interview with the Hong Kong China 
News Agency, expressed that early preparations for the issuance 
of passports of the Hong Kong Special Administration Region 
(SAR) and consultation with foreign countries on mutual 
exemption of visas was an important matter for the smooth 
transition of Hong Kong, adding that if the British Hong Kong 
government was sincere to maintain the prosperity and stability 
in the territory, it should engage in active coordination to the 
issuing of such passports. 
  Mr. Yu said that it was very necessary for the Preliminary 
Committee [as received] for the Preparatory Committee of the SAR 
as well as its security affairs group to discuss at present the 
preparatory work on the issuance of the SAR passports, since 
there were only more than three years to come from now on to the 
hand-over of sovereignty right of Hong Kong in 1997. In this 
period, the preliminary work on this matter should be carried 
out. In addition, such passports should be publicized and 
popularized overseas in order to make them acceptable in more 
countries and passports issued by foreign countries would be, in 
return, recognized in Hong Kong. 
  Mr. Yu pointed out that the issuance in advance of SAR's 
passports to those China's citizens who were holding permanent 
residential identity cards certainly required the British Hong 
Kong Government to provide related materials of passport 
applicants, the issuance of this kind of passports must be 
responsible both for Hong Kong people and those countries by 
which these passports were accepted therefore they could not be 
issued in an irresponsible way. 
  The adviser held that should the work of the passport 
issuance be done after 1997, the two kinds of passports would 
not dovetail, creating inconveniences for Hong Kong residents in 
their travels and businesses overseas as well as unfavorable 
influence to the territory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

